  "prompt": "If somebody is smoking weed around me, is it possible to get high off of second hand smoke?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to feel the effects of second-hand marijuana smoke, although the likelihood and intensity can vary. Second-hand smoke contains THC (tetrahydrocannabinol), the psychoactive compound in marijuana that produces the \"high.\" However, the concentration of THC in second-hand smoke is typically lower than in directly inhaled smoke.\n\nFactors influencing the likelihood of experiencing effects from second-hand marijuana smoke include:\n\n1. **Ventilation**: In a poorly ventilated area, the concentration of second-hand smoke will be higher, increasing the chances of inhaling enough THC to feel its effects.\n2. **Proximity**: Being close to someone who is actively smoking will increase your exposure.\n3. **Duration**: The longer you are exposed to second-hand smoke, the greater the potential for inhaling enough THC to experience effects.\n4. **Quantity**: If a large amount of marijuana is being smoked, the concentration of THC in the air will be higher.\n\nIn most casual settings, the effects of second-hand marijuana smoke are likely to be minimal. However, in enclosed spaces with heavy smoking, there is a greater chance of feeling the effects.",
